      <hedline>
        <hl1>The New Look of the Senate Race</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Eugene R Katz letter points out that Repr Rick Lazio failed opportunity to show courage and stand up to Republican leadership in matter of Pres Clinton's impeachment (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a moderate Democrat living in Suffolk County, I have followed the career of Representative Rick Lazio, now a candidate for senator from New York (front page, May 21), with great admiration -- that is, until President Clinton's impeachment.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a moderate Democrat living in Suffolk County, I have followed the career of Representative Rick Lazio, now a candidate for senator from New York (front page, May 21), with great admiration -- that is, until President Clinton's impeachment.</p>
        <p>As the impeachment vote drew close in the House and as most members declared on one side or the other, a bloc of moderate Republicans remained undecided and held the balance of power. One of their leaders was Mr. Lazio. Their indecision indicated that they had serious reservations about the impeachment, but they were under intense pressure from the Republican leadership. In the moment of truth, Mr. Lazio caved and took the bloc with him, with a couple of notable exceptions.</p>
        <p>Rick Lazio was given the opportunity to show courage and be a hero. He failed and showed that he was more beholden to his party than to the people.</p>
        <p>EUGENE R. KATZ  Stony Brook, N.Y., May 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
